<body>
    <entry id="2">
        <text>ille... illius... ille...</text>
        <references>1.7.3, 1.7.7, 1.9.1</references>
        <comment>Referring back to the &#60;span class='lt'&#62;&#60;a href="javascript:void(0)" onclick="quickHighlight('1.6.3')"&#62;deus&#60;/a&#62;&#60;/span&#62; (l. 6) to whom Tityrus attributes his new-found leisure.</comment>
    </entry>
    <entry id="3">
        <text>malum hoc</text>
        <references>1.16.2, 1.16.3</references>
        <comment>The death of the twin kids (&#60;span class='lt'&#62;gemellos&#60;/span&#62;) is the evil Meliboeus is referring to.</comment>
    </entry>
    <entry id="4">
        <text>de caelo tactas</text>
        <references>1.17.1, 1.17.2, 1.17.3</references>
        <comment>lit. "struck from the sky", i.e. "by lightning"</comment>
    </entry>
    <entry id="5">
        <text>Musam meditaris</text>
        <references>1.2.3, 1.2.4</references>
        <comment>&#60;span class='lt'&#62;&#60;a href="javascript:void(0)" onclick="quickHighlight('1.2.3--1.2.4')"&#62;Musam meditaris&#60;/a&#62;&#60;/span&#62; can mean either "you are considering the Muse", or "you are practising a song"</comment>
    </entry>
    <entry id="6">
        <text>Musam</text>
        <references>1.2.3</references>
        <comment>lit. "a Muse", hence metonymically "a song"</comment>
    </entry>
    <entry id="7">
        <text>tegmine</text>
        <references>1.1.6</references>
        <comment>abl. with &#60;span class='lt'&#62;&#60;a href="javascript:void(0)" onclick="quickHighlight('1.1.5')"&#62;sub&#60;/a&#62;&#60;/span&#62;; "under the cover..."</comment>
    </entry>
    <entry id="10">
        <text>sub</text>
        <references>1.1.5</references>
        <comment>with &#60;span class='lt'&#62;&#60;a href="javascript:void(0)" onclick="quickHighlight('1.1.6')"&#62;tegmine&#60;/a&#62;&#60;/span&#62;; "under the cover"</comment>
    </entry>
    <entry id="11">
        <text>various</text>
        <references>1.3.1, 1.3.6, 1.4.1, 1.4.3, 1.6.4, 1.8.3, 1.70.4</references>
        <comment>poetic plural</comment>
    </entry>
    <entry id="12">
        <text>ipsum</text>
        <references>1.9.8</references>
        <comment>reflexively referring to Tityrus</comment>
    </entry>
    <entry id="13">
        <text>permisit</text>
        <references>1.10.5</references>
        <comment>introduces two acc. + inf. indirect statements (&#60;span class='lt'&#62;&#60;a href="javascript:void(0)" onclick="quickHighlight('1.9.2--1.9.4')"&#62;meas errare boves&#60;/a&#62;&#60;/span&#62;; &#60;span class='lt'&#62;&#60;a href="javascript:void(0)" onclick="quickHighlight('1.9.8--1.10.1')"&#62;ipsum ludere&#60;/a&#62;&#60;/span&#62;)</comment>
    </entry>
    <entry id="14">
        <text>fugimus</text>
        <references>1.4.3</references>
        <comment>perfect or present</comment>
    </entry>
    <entry id="15">
        <text>turbatur</text>
        <references>1.12.3</references>
        <comment>impersonal - "there is disorder"</comment>
    </entry>
    <entry id="16">
        <text>usque adeo</text>
        <references>1.12.1, 1.12.2</references>
        <comment>&#60;span class='lt'&#62;&#60;a href="javascript:void(0)" onclick="quickHighlight('1.12.1--1.12.2')"&#62;usque adeo&#60;/a&#62;&#60;/span&#62; "to such an extent", "so much"</comment>
    </entry>
    <entry id="17">
        <text>ipse</text>
        <references>1.12.6</references>
        <comment>first person, reflexively referring to Meliboeus</comment>
    </entry>
    <entry id="18">
        <text>namque</text>
        <references>1.14.6</references>
        <comment>delayed in the line, explanatory and giving evidence for his previous statement</comment>
    </entry>
    <entry id="19">
        <text>namque</text>
        <references>1.14.6</references>
        <comment>Clausen (1970) pp. 85-6 suggests &#60;span class='lt'&#62;&#60;a href="javascript:void(0)" onclick="quickHighlight('1.14.6--1.14.7')"&#62;namque gemellos&#60;/a&#62;&#60;/span&#62; was in imitation of Catullus' &#60;span class='lt'&#62;namque Leonis&#60;/span&#62; (66.65)</comment>
    </entry>
    <entry id="20">
        <text>causa videndi</text>
        <references>1.27.7, 1.27.8</references>
        <comment>&#60;span class='lt'&#62;&#60;a href="javascript:void(0)" onclick="quickHighlight('1.27.7--1.27.8')"&#62;causa vivendi&#60;/a&#62;&#60;/span&#62; - "reason for seeing"</comment>
    </entry>
    <entry id="21">
        <text>postquam nos Amaryllis habet, Galatea reliquit</text>
        <references>1.31.1, 1.31.2, 1.31.3, 1.31.4, 1.31.5, 1.31.6</references>
        <comment>&#60;span class='lt'&#62;&#60;a href="javascript:void(0)" onclick="quickHighlight('1.31.3--1.31.4')"&#62;Amaryllis habet&#60;/a&#62;&#60;/span&#62; and &#60;span class='lt'&#62;&#60;a href="javascript:void(0)" onclick="quickHighlight('1.31.5--1.31.6')"&#62;Galatea reliquit&#60;/a&#62;&#60;/span&#62; are in apposition: "after Amaryllis held me, and Galatea left me"</comment>
    </entry>
    <entry id="22">
        <text>sua… arbore</text>
        <references>1.38.3, 1.38.6</references>
        <comment>&#60;span class='lt'&#62;&#60;a href="javascript:void(0)" onclick="quickHighlight('1.38.3')"&#62;sua&#60;/a&#62;&#60;/span&#62; refers to the tree (&#60;span class='lt'&#62;&#60;a href="javascript:void(0)" onclick="quickHighlight('1.38.6')"&#62;arbore&#60;/a&#62;&#60;/span&#62;): "[the tree's] fruits in the tree"</comment>
    </entry>
    <entry id="23">
        <text>mirabar, quid… cui…</text>
        <references>1.37.1, 1.37.2, 1.38.1</references>
        <comment>&#60;span class='lt'&#62;&#60;a href="javascript:void(0)" onclick="quickHighlight('1.37.1')"&#62;mirabar&#60;/a&#62;&#60;/span&#62; introduces two indirect questions (which are in apposition) with &#60;span class='lt'&#62;&#60;a href="javascript:void(0)" onclick="quickHighlight('1.37.2')"&#62;quid&#60;/a&#62;&#60;/span&#62; and &#60;span class='lt'&#62;&#60;a href="javascript:void(0)" onclick="quickHighlight('1.38.1')"&#62;cui&#60;/a&#62;&#60;/span&#62;: "I was wondering why... [and] for whom"</comment>
    </entry>
    <entry id="24">
        <text>ante… ante… quam</text>
        <references>1.60.1, 1.62.1, 1.64.1</references>
        <comment>&#60;span class='lt'&#62;ante&#60;/span&#62; at &#60;a href="javascript:void(0)" onclick="quickHighlight('1.60.1')"&#62;60&#60;/a&#62; and &#60;a href="javascript:void(0)" onclick="quickHighlight('1.62.1')"&#62;62&#60;/a&#62; anticipate &#60;span class='lt'&#62;&#60;a href="javascript:void(0)" onclick="quickHighlight('1.64.1')"&#62;quam&#60;/a&#62;&#60;/span&#62;; like a usual &#60;span class='lt'&#62;antequam&#60;/span&#62; temporal clause, leave aside the &#60;span class='lt'&#62;ante&#60;/span&#62;, and translate &#60;span class='lt'&#62;quam&#60;/span&#62; as "after"</comment>
    </entry>
    <entry id="25">
        <text>alii… pars</text>
        <references>1.65.4, 1.66.1	</references>
        <comment>like &#60;span class='lt'&#62;alii… alii… &#60;/span&#62; or &#60;span class='lt'&#62;pars… pars… &#60;/span&#62;, &#60;span class='lt'&#62;&#60;a href="javascript:void(0)" onclick="quickHighlight('1.65.4')"&#62;alii&#60;/a&#62;&#60;/span&#62; and &#60;span class='lt'&#62;&#60;a href="javascript:void(0)" onclick="quickHighlight('1.66.1')"&#62;pars&#60;/a&#62;&#60;/span&#62; are "some... others..."</comment>
    </entry>
    <entry id="26">
        <text>caespite</text>
        <references>1.69.5</references>
        <comment>turf (&#60;span class='lt'&#62;&#60;a href="javascript:void(0)" onclick="quickHighlight('1.69.5')"&#62;caespite&#60;/a&#62;&#60;/span&#62;) was used as a building material</comment>
    </entry>
    <entry id="28">
        <text>ordine</text>
        <references>1.74.6</references>
        <comment>"in rows"</comment>
    </entry>
    <entry id="29">
        <text>fronde</text>
        <references>1.81.1</references>
        <comment>used here as bedding</comment>
    </entry>
    <entry id="30">
        <text>habet… reliquit</text>
        <references>1.31.4, 1.31.6</references>
        <comment>historic present</comment>
    </entry>
